\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 title: Product launch email: best practices with 23 examples\
slug: product-launch-email\
meta des: Discover what makes a great product launch email for SaaS. See real examples, proven strategies, and templates to boost engagement and conversions.\
Product launch emails are your chance to rally your audience around something new\'97whether it's a shiny new product, a feature update, or an upcoming release.\
But writing a compelling product launch email isn\'92t just about listing features. It\'92s about building anticipation, communicating value clearly, and getting people excited to take action.\
In this article, we\'92ll break down what makes a great product launch email and how to write one that actually converts.\
I\'92ll walk you through real-world examples\'97including a smart launch from Notion\'97so you can see what works and how to apply it to your own launches.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 The different types of product launch\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf0 Soft vs hard product launch: what\'92s the difference?\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 A soft launch is like testing the waters\'97it\'92s lower risk, lower pressure, and often used to gather feedback or validate assumptions. You might send a teaser email, open early access to a few subscribers, or promote quietly on your blog.\
A hard launch is a bigger play: it usually involves coordinated marketing messages, a defined launch date, and a product launch {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.digistorms.com/blog/lifecycle-email-marketing"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 email sequence}} to current and potential customers. Both can be effective\'97it just depends on your goals.\
Are you still iterating? Go soft. Are you ready to scale and grab attention? Time to go hard and bring out your launch email template.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 When to go feature-first vs product-first in launch messaging\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 A product-first launch email puts the spotlight on the whole product\'97great for big rollouts, new product lines, or complete redesigns. You\'92re pitching the big picture. A feature-first approach zooms in on a specific update or improvement.\
It\'92s ideal when you\'92re building on an existing product and want to {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.digistorms.com/blog/saas-gamification"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 encourage engagement}} or highlight a new capability. If your audience already uses the product, lead with the feature. If you\'92re introducing something brand new, go product-first.\
Either way, your email subject line and email body should clearly state the value\'97don\'92t just describe what\'92s new, explain why your reader should care.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

